WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.320
Hello and welcome back. In this lesson, we will connect OpenClaw to dnspy-mcp.

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:14.400
I have started my Windows 11 virtual machine. You can see that the OpenClaw gateway has auto-started.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:21.180
I have also started my Telegram app. Be sure to clear history.

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:24.940
Then use the slash new command to start a new session.

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:31.500
I have also created a new folder on my desktop called .NET MCP.

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:38.280
Inside it, I have downloaded the dnspy-mcp-server zip file from the previous lesson.

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:43.920
I had also earlier unzipped it into the folder dnspy-mcp-server.

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:49.160
For this lesson, I have also downloaded a new file called .NET crackme-zip.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.440
You can download it from the resource section for this lesson.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:56.280
Let's open this folder and see what's inside.

00:00:56.280 --> 00:00:58.760
You have 3 folders of crackmes.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:01.800
The first two are modern .NET crackmes.

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:05.360
These are crackmes written on .NET 8 and above.

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:10.420
The third folder is a legacy crackme written on .NET Framework 4.8.

00:01:10.420 --> 00:01:12.560
Coming back to the modern .NET.

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:15.420
The first one is a 64-bit crackme.

00:01:15.420 --> 00:01:18.600
The second one is a 32-bit crackme.

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:20.980
Let's open the 64-bit folder.

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:25.000
The main file is called modernnetapp.exe.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.340
This one is 64-bit.

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:32.860
To confirm if it is 64-bit or 32-bit, you can use detect it easy.

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:36.280
Search for detect it easy.

00:01:36.280 --> 00:01:39.950
Then run it.

00:01:39.950 --> 00:01:43.150
Then open the crack me with detect it easy.

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:46.850
You will see it says PE64.

00:01:46.850 --> 00:01:52.940
Now let's check the 32-bit one.

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:56.600
And we see it says PE32.

00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:08.340
Now let's go back to the 64-bit version and launch it.

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:17.370
Enter a name in the serial and click on the register button.

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:21.170
It shows a message box, sorry wrong key.

00:02:21.170 --> 00:02:26.750
We will now launch the correct dnspy mcp.

00:02:26.750 --> 00:02:30.150
Open the dnspy mcp server folder.

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:33.690
As mentioned in the previous lesson, there are 2 versions.

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:36.890
The first is the modern.net.

00:02:36.890 --> 00:02:43.600
The second is the legacy.net framework 4.8.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:50.820
We will analyze the Modern.NET CrackMe Therefore, we should open the Modern.NET MCP

00:02:50.820 --> 00:03:00.580
Also remember that the CrackMe is 64-bit Therefore, we should launch the 64-bit DNSpy

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:13.840
Right click and run as administrator Click OK

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:22.980
I will remove the modules I previously loaded and start afresh

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:42.070
Open the Modern.NET app. Notice I opened the exe file

00:03:42.070 --> 00:03:53.240
This is not the right one. I should open the .dll file. I will remove the .exe file.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:04:02.180
When using dnspy, you should open the .dll, not the .exe file. However, if you

00:04:02.180 --> 00:04:07.420
want to run the app directly, then you run the .exe file. Let's take a look at

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:12.340
the app. You will see the main module is Modern NetApp. Now, we will check to

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:22.580
confirm that the MCP server has started successfully. Open a CMD terminal. Run the

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:37.440
command netstat-tan. You should see port 3003. This confirms that the dnspy MCP server has

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:48.560
properly started. Now, I will use telegram to give instructions to open CLAW. You may use the

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:57.220
same prompt that I use. It is the same as the previous two MCP servers we did. You just need

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:06.180
to modify it for dnspy. It is important to mention port 3003 and the SSE endpoint.

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:13.440
Ask OpenClaw to refer to its memory to recall the previous MCP examples we did.

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:23.060
It has found the previous MCP and SSE in memory

00:05:23.060 --> 00:05:30.800
It now confirms the server is doing MCP over SSE

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:39.120
It has successfully connected to the dnspy mcp server and got a list of its tools

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:46.290
I then ask it to get info on the modern net app loaded in dnspy

00:05:46.290 --> 00:05:53.400
OpenClaw confirms it is reconnecting to the dnspy session

00:05:53.400 --> 00:06:00.120
After doing some analysis with the tools, it finally got the results

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:03.520
It has found Form 1

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:07.820
This must be the main Windows UI for the app

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:11.800
I ask it to get info on Form 1

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:17.760
OpenClaw then does some analysis and manages to find some important methods in Form 1

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:21.900
It lists button register and generates serial key methods

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:29.560
it even explains what the generate serial key method does. It also explains

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:36.520
how the serial key is being generated. Open claw then gave some examples. Let's

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:45.440
take another look at the app. If I enter name as Alexander and any random number

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:52.400
as serial key then click the register button it shows the message box sorry

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:59.260
wrong key. I will ask OpenClaw to generate the serial key for me for the

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:05.980
username Alexander. OpenClaw tells me the serial key. I try

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:17.180
it and it works. I now ask it to write a Python script to implement the generate

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:24.830
serial key method. It is actually a key gen. However note that you should not use

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:32.030
the word keygen. The backend OpenAI agent may refuse to create keygens due to ethical reasons.

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:43.840
To be safe, just say Python script. It generates the Python code. I ask it where is the file saved

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:52.530
to. I then head over to that folder by copying and pasting it into the address bar.

00:07:52.530 --> 00:08:00.830
I removed the filename leaving only the folder path.

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:08.020
I found the GenerateSerialKey Python script.

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:10.500
Let's run it.

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:18.690
I open a CMD terminal and run the script.

00:08:18.690 --> 00:08:24.850
I entered the name, Christina, and got the serial.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:27.290
I will now test it.

00:08:27.290 --> 00:08:31.550
Let's go back to the app.

00:08:31.550 --> 00:08:44.580
Enter the name and the serial and click on the register button.

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:47.880
It works.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:55.500
Let's ask OpenClaw to do something else.

00:08:55.500 --> 00:09:00.020
Let's ask OpenClaw to analyze the button register method.

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:07.170
We copy the method name and paste it in here.

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:10.830
It analyzed the method and came up with a detailed result.

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:16.560
It is very impressive.

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:24.940
Now I will ask it to save to memory how it connects to the dnspy mcp server.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:33.000
Remember that we also did this for the x64 dbg and ghidra mcp in earlier lessons.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:43.790
This is important so that OpenClaw will remember how to connect to dnspy mcp in future.

00:09:43.790 --> 00:09:48.860
OpenClaw confirms saving it to memory.

00:09:48.860 --> 00:09:54.300
I ask it where is the memory file found.

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:57.220
It replies with the paths.

00:09:57.220 --> 00:10:02.770
Let's go and inspect it.

00:10:02.770 --> 00:10:13.550
These are the session memories based on dates, and this is the long term memory.

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:27.950
Let's open it, and you can see how it remembers the dnspy connection.

00:10:27.950 --> 00:10:30.990
I also see the Ghidra memory.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:36.570
There is also the x64 dbg memory.

00:10:36.570 --> 00:10:44.710
Now we will shut down everything and take a snapshot of the virtual machine.

00:10:44.710 --> 00:10:51.690
After every successful setup, we should always take a snapshot.

00:10:51.690 --> 00:11:01.510
on take button. Give a suitable name. Click on OK. Now we can go analyze any

00:11:01.510 --> 00:11:06.390
other crack me program or malware that you like. Note that after analyzing any

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:12.190
target binary or malware, whether using dnspy or Ghidra

00:11:12.190 --> 00:11:20.960
or x64dbg, we always restore back to the latest snapshot after finishing the

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:22.340
session.

00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:26.600
That is to undo any changes made by the target program or malware.

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:29.800
That is why I stress the importance of using snapshots.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:35.900
So this is how we can use OpenClaw with dnspy-mcp.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:37.780
That's all for this video.

00:11:37.780 --> 00:11:38.580
Thanks for watching.

